Boil a full #kettle{}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 3cm chunks.

Pour the boiled water from your kettle into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat. Add the @basmati rice{150} and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{}, then pop it on top of the pan and allow to steam until ready to serve.

Heat a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240} and pepper chunks and fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. 

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once the mince has browned, add the garlic and @harissa paste{50} to the pan. Cook until fragrant, ~{30%secs}.

Stir in the @chicken stock paste{10} and @water for the beef{100}.

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir the @peas{120}, @honey{1} and @butter{20} through the cooked rice until piping hot and melted, ~{1%minute}.

Add the cooked rice and @sun-dried tomato paste{25} to the pan of spicy mince and stir to combine.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of water if a little dry.

When ready, share the beef pilaf between your #bowls{}.

Enjoy!